it isn't better to just remove them?
I don't really want to break everyones forks that might be using this.
Can we set a date to remove these?

FWIW, My long term goal is to get rid of UnpackVariant altogether.  I don't think the "Need to explicitly declare every possible type to unpack" paradigm meshes well with bmcweb, and I suspect unduly causes thrash in people that want to use the code.  Ideally we wouldn't have to be making core utility changes to unpack a new type.

It was done originally because it significantly dropped the binary size, given how many readJson calls we had, but as we've been dropping those calls and cleaning this stuff up, it's making the variant itself less and less relevant (we could probably survive the binary size increase if we removed it today, but I haven't measured).

This is the long winded way of saying, I don't really want to put a date here;  It doesn't hurt anything to have, aside from people being able to write less than optimal code

> This is the long winded way of saying, I don't really want to put a date here; It doesn't hurt anything to have, aside from people being able to write less than optimal code

I guess, I would rather we have a date and remove some day. 
1. Less code we carry (even though not  a lot)
2. Like we do elsewhere when we enhance the code base, force forks to follow better code when they rebase
3. We know for sure, no one ever uses upstream (yep I know we can look for it in reivews..)
Added a date.  You arguments are reasonable.
I am fine with this. I would rather a date and remove in 6 months or a year but shrug, not a big deal.
